01:01.918 --> 01:04.334
So, Pat, she's gonna faint.

01:04.459 --> 01:06.793
Okay? And then you pull her up like this.

01:06.918 --> 01:09.043
- Keep this very strong.
- Yeah.

01:09.209 --> 01:11.418
Pelvis close and go for the kiss. Watch this.

01:11.543 --> 01:13.501
Clive, okay, I have read the script.

01:13.626 --> 01:15.209
Something like this?

01:16.126 --> 01:19.251
- I've got you.
- You've got me all right.

01:23.876 --> 01:25.668
Save it for the take, baby.

01:25.751 --> 01:28.501
- Plenty more where that came from.
- That was okay.

01:28.668 --> 01:30.584
But don't open your mouth when you kiss,

01:30.709 --> 01:32.959
because it spreads germs all around the set.

01:33.084 --> 01:37.043
- When you're acting, purse your lips...
- Clive, Clive!

01:37.209 --> 01:38.751
We weren't acting.

01:38.876 --> 01:40.876
- I was acting.
- What?

01:41.543 --> 01:44.709
Ooh, hoo, hoo! Hello!

01:44.834 --> 01:45.793
Pow!

01:45.918 --> 01:48.959
This little firecracker is
the real star of Mindhorn.

01:49.084 --> 01:52.251
- Maybe I could get more lines next time.
- That's a good one!

01:52.376 --> 01:55.751
- That's your handbrake there.
- Okay, walk away, Clive.

01:55.876 --> 01:57.668
Ready to shoot.

01:57.793 --> 01:59.501
Shoes, Clive!

01:59.626 --> 02:02.501
Shoes coming in. Shoes are safe.

02:05.959 --> 02:07.709
Shoes going on.

02:08.709 --> 02:10.043
Shoes on.

02:11.709 --> 02:13.376
Okay, let's go.

02:14.668 --> 02:17.001
Okay, guys, first positions.

02:17.126 --> 02:19.376
- You know I love you.
- Turn over.

02:19.501 --> 02:22.251
- I love you too, honey.
- Sound running.

02:22.376 --> 02:23.793
- Truth time.
- Action!

02:24.918 --> 02:28.501
'In 1983, Special Agent
Bruce P Mindhorn was captured

02:28.626 --> 02:30.918
'during a secret operation
on the Siberian border.

02:31.584 --> 02:35.001
'Communist doctors performed
experimental cybernetic surgery upon him.

02:35.126 --> 02:40.209
'They removed his eye and replaced it
with a super-advanced optical lie detector

02:40.334 --> 02:44.293
'which meant he could
literally see the truth.

02:44.876 --> 02:48.334
'He escaped Russia
and returned home to the Isle of Man.

02:50.293 --> 02:52.959
'Bruce Mindhorn became
the best plain-clothes detective

02:53.084 --> 02:55.709
'the Isle of Man had ever seen.

02:56.376 --> 02:59.918
'In a world of lies, one man has had enough.

03:01.334 --> 03:04.793
'You can't hide the truth from Mindhorn.'

03:09.293 --> 03:12.876
'Richard Thorncroft is an actor
on the crest of a wave.'

03:13.001 --> 03:16.876
'Richard, he's strong
and sprints like a panther.'

03:18.793 --> 03:22.584
'Acting is 95% physicality.

03:23.626 --> 03:25.459
'That's why I practise Capoeira.'

03:26.751 --> 03:29.751
'Here we see Richard demonstrating the Ginga

03:29.834 --> 03:32.043
'that gives him flexibility as an actor.'

03:32.209 --> 03:36.459
Your mouth's saying no,
but your brain's saying yes.

03:36.584 --> 03:40.293
'In real life, Richard's eye
has fallen on part-time actress

03:40.376 --> 03:43.043
'and full-time lovely, Patricia Deville.'

03:43.209 --> 03:45.626
'Richard and I are a wonderful team,

03:45.709 --> 03:50.043
'both at work and hopefully in life forever.'

03:50.251 --> 03:52.084
'Such is the success of Mindhorn,

03:52.251 --> 03:54.709
'it's rumoured that Windjammer
played by Peter Easterman

03:54.834 --> 03:57.001
'may even get his own show.'

03:58.793 --> 04:03.876
'Er, no, I can't envisage
any kind of spin-off.'

04:04.001 --> 04:07.501
'Spin-offs or not,
Richard's star is burning bright

04:07.626 --> 04:10.334
'thanks to publicity genius
Jeffrey Moncrief.'

04:10.459 --> 04:13.793
'We work hard on Mindhorn,
but we play hard too.

04:13.918 --> 04:16.793
'Sometimes too hard. Hello, rehab!'

04:17.793 --> 04:21.709
'To stay at the top, you need to be
remarkable on screen and off,

04:21.834 --> 04:24.626
'and Richard certainly knows
how to play that game.'

04:25.126 --> 04:27.501
The Isle of Man is a... hole.

04:27.626 --> 04:28.834
What?

04:30.084 --> 04:32.293
Peter Easterman is not a great actor.

04:33.043 --> 04:37.751
But when he is acting, at least
he stands there and does stuff.

04:37.876 --> 04:40.418
'Whether Richard's winning awards for acting

04:40.543 --> 04:43.418
'or courting controversy
on top-rated chat shows

04:43.543 --> 04:47.418
'it seems nothing can stop him
heading all the way to the top.'

04:47.584 --> 04:49.626
'I'm going to Hollywood. Bye.'

05:02.501 --> 05:04.418
'Police in the Isle of Man
say they have discovered

05:04.543 --> 05:07.751
'the body of a young woman
washed up on Douglas Beach.'

05:07.876 --> 05:10.876
'Police are treating
Katya Lipinskii's death as murder.'

05:13.043 --> 05:16.709
'Police confirm they have received
phone calls from the suspect,

05:16.793 --> 05:19.626
'but have refused to divulge the content.'

05:40.709 --> 05:42.834
It's Plasticine.

05:43.959 --> 05:45.293
It's here.

05:51.334 --> 05:53.626
- Hello.
- 'I've told you before.

05:53.709 --> 05:57.834
'There's only one person I will speak to:
Detective Mindhorn.'

05:57.959 --> 06:00.043
- Melly?
- 'My name is the Kestrel.'

06:00.209 --> 06:02.334
Sorry, sorry, sorry.

06:03.251 --> 06:05.418
- The Kestrel.
- 'Thank you.

06:05.543 --> 06:08.043
'I'll call the police station
tomorrow at 4:00pm.

06:08.209 --> 06:10.918
'If I'm not talking
to Detective Mindhorn in person,

06:11.043 --> 06:13.001
'more people are going to die.

06:13.126 --> 06:15.418
'Signing off.'

06:20.084 --> 06:23.043
- Chief?
- Oh, great.

06:23.209 --> 06:26.584
Our chief suspect wants to talk
to a fictional fucking detective.

06:29.251 --> 06:32.043
Mindhorn! It was fucking shite an' all.

06:33.918 --> 06:35.584
'Heard of haemotracteathosis?'

06:35.709 --> 06:39.126
'I think it was on the menu
at my local Indian restaurant last night.'

06:40.418 --> 06:42.918
'Bruce, let me help you with this case.'

06:43.043 --> 06:44.959
'I told you before, I work alone.'

06:45.084 --> 06:47.126
What are we going to do, Chief?

06:47.334 --> 06:50.251
We got 24 hours to produce
a convincing Detective Mindhorn.

06:50.376 --> 06:54.418
We're going to have to bring
the actor over to take the call.

06:54.543 --> 06:57.293
- Let's think about this.
- Green's right.

06:57.418 --> 07:00.251
Believe me, I wish that he wasn't.

07:00.334 --> 07:02.584
Get me Mindhorn.

07:04.668 --> 07:06.668
'It's truth time.'

07:13.876 --> 07:17.959
Baboons. Baboons bring bliss.

07:18.084 --> 07:20.959
The Benedict Cumberbatch backlash has begun.

07:25.959 --> 07:29.584
You are exactly where you need to be.

07:34.251 --> 07:37.376
You are a powerful tiger.

07:38.251 --> 07:41.918
Let's do this!

07:42.001 --> 07:44.918
- Bugger, bugger.
- Oi, keep it down, will you?

07:45.043 --> 07:47.501
- Sorry.
- What are you doing in there?

07:52.334 --> 07:54.668
# You can't handcuff the wind

07:57.543 --> 08:00.293
Ah, hello, lovely. Here for the casting.
Richard Thorncroft.

08:00.418 --> 08:03.668
Oh, great. Mr Branagh's
nearly ready for you, Richard...

08:03.751 --> 08:05.876
- Crowthorne?
- Thorncroft.

08:06.001 --> 08:08.709
The B-Man! Kenny B!

08:10.043 --> 08:12.293
Bloody good to see you!

08:12.918 --> 08:14.834
Let's crack this baby open.

08:17.668 --> 08:20.501
Hi. Richard Crowthorne, 11 o'clock.

08:21.543 --> 08:22.584
Oh.

08:23.626 --> 08:24.751
Right.

08:24.876 --> 08:27.126
I speak the truth!

08:27.334 --> 08:29.709
I am afeared of no man.

08:29.834 --> 08:32.083
I am afeared of no creature.

08:32.251 --> 08:34.251
I am my own man.

08:34.376 --> 08:37.333
I am Clifton of Port Antonio.

08:37.458 --> 08:39.083
Do you feel me?

08:40.708 --> 08:43.668
Yeah, that's incredible.
That's literally incredible.

08:43.751 --> 08:45.626
Thank you.

08:45.709 --> 08:47.543
You're welcome, really.

08:47.626 --> 08:49.584
I don't know what to say, but thank you.

08:49.668 --> 08:51.084
I want to try something.

08:51.293 --> 08:53.876
I'd like to do it again,
but this time with a brogue.

08:54.001 --> 08:56.626
No, I think we're good. We've got everything.

08:56.709 --> 08:58.959
I've seen everything I could possibly want.

08:59.043 --> 09:01.084
- Are you sure?
- Oh, yeah.

09:01.251 --> 09:05.293
Well, acting aside,
it's been great to catch up.

09:05.376 --> 09:08.709
Kenny B! This guy was
one crazy hombre back in the day.

09:08.793 --> 09:13.126
- Remember that hotel in Maidstone?
- Oh, who can forget that?

09:13.293 --> 09:16.793
We did a tour of the Medway Basin,
and this fella...

09:16.918 --> 09:19.918
Well, they'll have to repaper
that hotel room.

09:20.043 --> 09:22.959
I love what you're doing these days.
Ken, I admire your balls.

09:23.793 --> 09:25.959
Okay. The B-Man!

09:26.084 --> 09:28.418
- All righty.
- The Killer B!

09:29.584 --> 09:31.209
The Bran Flake!

09:32.959 --> 09:35.751
- Who was that?
- Not a fucking clue.

09:36.543 --> 09:38.043
Hey, brother.

09:38.251 --> 09:40.709
You got my details? Lovely.

09:47.584 --> 09:50.793
'Sorry, Sarah. Front desk
say Richard Thorncroft is here.'

09:50.918 --> 09:53.626
Oh, Christ. I'm with Simon.
Tell him to wait outside.

09:54.334 --> 09:56.584
Ah, Richard, darling. How are you?

09:56.709 --> 09:58.293
'It's too late. I couldn't stop him.'

09:58.418 --> 10:01.501
How am I? Let me think.
I haven't had an audition in 18 months.

10:01.584 --> 10:03.793
And you put me up for a schizophrenic yardie.

10:03.918 --> 10:07.459
- Sounds like a good part to me.
- If you're a 60-year-old Jamaican man.

10:07.584 --> 10:10.084
I'm so sorry, Simon.
I didn't realise it was you.

10:10.251 --> 10:12.793
Big fan, big fan.
Caught your Equus in Chichester.

10:12.918 --> 10:15.459
- Powerful piece of work.
- Great, thank you.

10:15.584 --> 10:17.959
And you were fantastic in, um...

10:18.084 --> 10:20.293
Oh, God, my memory's gone these days.

10:20.418 --> 10:22.543
- Anyway, you were fantastic.
- Thank you.

10:22.668 --> 10:24.709
Sorry about the cock-up. New assistant.

10:24.834 --> 10:27.293
How can you mix me up with Crowthorne?
Do I not exist anymore?

10:27.418 --> 10:30.459
- No one seems to know who I am.
- Me and the Branster go way back.

10:30.584 --> 10:32.668
- I don't suppose you could...
- Simon sweetie...

10:32.751 --> 10:34.626
Could you just give us a few moments?

10:34.709 --> 10:37.251
- I could have this salad.
- Come back, two minutes.

10:40.126 --> 10:43.418
- What the hell's going on?
- You're going through a transitional phase.

10:43.543 --> 10:45.084
You said that five years ago, Sarah.

10:45.251 --> 10:47.918
I mean, you're moving
from young, handsome hero

10:48.043 --> 10:50.668
to older, still very handsome...

10:50.751 --> 10:54.376
What about my autobiography?
Are there any takers, any bites?

10:54.501 --> 10:57.084
'It's a quiet time
for actors' autobiographies.'

10:57.251 --> 10:59.418
It's not very quiet for Peter Easterman.

10:59.543 --> 11:01.376
No, I don't think so. Volume three?

11:01.543 --> 11:04.418
What's this one called?
"What I Did Yesterday"? Ha!

11:04.543 --> 11:06.459
Windjammer's on its 16th season.

11:06.584 --> 11:08.293
'He's built a franchise.

11:08.418 --> 11:11.251
'He's even got his own range
of weatherproof clothing.'

11:11.334 --> 11:13.751
I did not get into this business
to sell kagoules.

11:13.876 --> 11:17.126
- Well, you've got to sell something.
- Sell this, hmm?

11:17.293 --> 11:20.584
This is a map of human emotion. Sell it!

11:20.709 --> 11:22.709
Nobody can. You haven't got profile.

11:22.793 --> 11:25.293
That's why you made me
do the Thrombi-Sox ads.

11:25.459 --> 11:28.084
To give me profile.
Thank God for Thrombi-Sox.

11:28.251 --> 11:30.584
And that is not a sentence
I thought I'd ever utter.

11:30.709 --> 11:32.418
About Thrombi-Sox...

11:32.918 --> 11:35.376
- What?
- They've gone in a different direction.

11:35.501 --> 11:37.376
'John fucking Nettle?'

11:37.459 --> 11:39.709
'You told the director he was an embryo.'

11:39.834 --> 11:41.626
'Well, he's about 12.'

11:41.709 --> 11:44.418
Sit down and calm down. Come on.

11:44.543 --> 11:47.671
All is not lost.
I had a very interesting offer for you.

11:47.751 --> 11:50.251
- An offer?
- From the police.

11:50.834 --> 11:53.418
- What do you mean?
- They want you to talk to a suspect...

11:53.584 --> 11:56.001
See if you can lure him into custody.

11:56.084 --> 11:58.668
What, so this is a voiceover or something?

11:58.793 --> 12:00.918
Yeah, a bit like a voiceover.

12:01.043 --> 12:03.668
- 'He thinks Mindhorn is a real detective.'
- 'What?'

12:03.751 --> 12:05.001
Mindhorn! That was it.

12:05.126 --> 12:07.418
You were wonderful. That was your Amadeus.

12:07.543 --> 12:09.543
Well, I mean, Amadeus was my Amadeus.

12:09.668 --> 12:13.626
'Fuck off, Callow! This is a private
conversation with my agent!'

12:13.709 --> 12:15.584
Just calm down and sit down.

12:15.709 --> 12:18.043
- I don't want to sit down.
- Then stand up, but calm down.

12:18.209 --> 12:19.668
I'll sit down.

12:19.751 --> 12:21.084
Sit down, then.

12:21.251 --> 12:23.793
Okay, so let's focus on this Mindhorn thing.

12:23.918 --> 12:26.584
- I was bloody good in Mindhorn.
- You'll be even better now.

12:26.709 --> 12:29.084
You've matured like a fine wine.

12:29.251 --> 12:31.834
- A man could get drunk on that wine.
- Great.

12:31.959 --> 12:34.084
So go to the Isle of Man, take the call...

12:34.293 --> 12:36.709
- Sorry, where?
- The Isle of Man.

12:36.834 --> 12:40.126
This isn't going to work for me.
I do not go backwards in my career.

12:40.293 --> 12:42.709
- I move ever forwards...
- Like a shark.

12:42.793 --> 12:45.793
Yes, but maybe going backwards
is the new going forwards.

12:46.334 --> 12:48.334
Why don't you hook up with the old gang?

12:49.251 --> 12:51.959
Jeffrey Moncrief has got his own PR firm now.

12:52.084 --> 12:54.668
Jeffrey Moncrief?
He went off the rails, I'm afraid.

12:54.751 --> 12:56.543
Looks kosher to me.

12:56.668 --> 12:59.501
You need all the publicity
you can get from this.

12:59.626 --> 13:02.084
What about Pat Deville, your old flame?

13:02.251 --> 13:05.834
Works for Manx TV now. Profile, Richard.

13:05.918 --> 13:09.251
'Imagine: TV cop helps real cop solve crime.

13:09.376 --> 13:11.834
'It's PR gold. You'd be a hero!

13:11.959 --> 13:15.209
'Do the interviews, get in the papers,
remind people who you are,

13:15.293 --> 13:17.084
'and bang, you're back on the map.

13:17.251 --> 13:20.043
'Just play Mindhorn one last time.'

13:27.043 --> 13:28.459
Profile!

13:56.834 --> 13:58.793
'Isle of Man Constabulary.'

13:58.918 --> 14:01.334
- I'm in.
- 'Sorry, who is this?'

14:06.668 --> 14:10.501
'Hello. Moncrief Public Relations
International Limited.'

14:10.626 --> 14:13.834
- Jeff!
- 'Richie! Are you here?'

14:13.959 --> 14:16.501
Yep, I'm here.
Two o'clock ferry, like we said.

14:16.626 --> 14:19.834
- Where are you?
- 'I'm working my butt off here for you.

14:19.959 --> 14:23.834
'Why don't I see you at the police station
once I finish up here at the office?'

14:23.959 --> 14:26.293
Okay, sounds good. What about the newspapers?

14:26.418 --> 14:28.376
The Manx Express loves it.

14:28.501 --> 14:33.209
They're sending a photographer
to get some shots of you doing the call.

14:33.334 --> 14:37.418
Now, we've got to get to Pat
at Manx TV before she knocks off.

14:37.543 --> 14:41.209
You know what? I think I might have time
to squeeze that in before the gig.

14:41.376 --> 14:43.709
I bet you have, you devil!

14:43.793 --> 14:45.876
'Hey, come on!

14:46.001 --> 14:50.043
She's not married
and you're the thinking woman's crumpet!

14:50.126 --> 14:51.918
Bye, Jeff.

14:52.043 --> 14:53.418
Ahoy, there!

14:54.709 --> 14:58.709
This is the old stomping ground,
back in the old wild-oats-sowing days.

14:58.793 --> 15:01.084
Yeah, there's very good soil here.

15:01.251 --> 15:03.626
'Welcome to the Isle of Man,

15:03.709 --> 15:07.584
'isle of adventure, isle of romance...
I'll have some of that!'

15:07.709 --> 15:11.918
- Mr Thorncroft, DS Baines.
- Enchanté. Call me Richard.

15:12.001 --> 15:14.709
PC Green and I will be
overseeing your stay here.

15:14.793 --> 15:16.876
- Roger that.
- We really appreciate this.

15:17.001 --> 15:19.543
- I know you're a busy man.
- I had to move things around.

15:19.668 --> 15:22.376
But work is work. This is more important.

15:22.501 --> 15:23.959
Let's save some lives.

15:25.084 --> 15:26.709
- This us?
- Yeah, yeah.

15:34.959 --> 15:36.209
Thanks.

15:38.209 --> 15:39.793
- You in?
- Yeah, yeah, great.

15:42.001 --> 15:44.251
Melly thought Mindhorn was real.

15:44.334 --> 15:48.209
Yeah, well, three years at RADA
give a man some skills.

15:48.334 --> 15:50.501
- Were you a fan of the show?
- My mum liked it.

15:50.584 --> 15:53.126
Ah, a woman of taste.

15:53.293 --> 15:55.834
- Is she single?
- She's dead.

15:55.959 --> 15:58.959
We'll give you a knock in 20 minutes.

15:59.084 --> 16:02.043
- Lovely.
- Stay in the room for your safety.

16:02.209 --> 16:04.126
Sure thing, big guy.

16:17.209 --> 16:19.834
- You gonna be there the whole time?
- That's right.

16:19.959 --> 16:22.709
Good, really good news.

16:22.793 --> 16:26.709
I'm gonna be doing some meditating, so...

16:26.834 --> 16:28.376
- Do you meditate?
- No.

16:28.501 --> 16:30.376
- Something to think about.
- Thanks.

16:30.501 --> 16:32.543
Sorry about your mum.

16:33.668 --> 16:34.876
Shit!

16:52.626 --> 16:54.126
I'm just meeting someone here.

16:54.293 --> 16:57.293
- She let you do that to her?
- Not for the first time.

16:57.418 --> 17:00.834
Anyway, download that footage
and get that sent over.

17:00.959 --> 17:04.709
Yeah, it's an offer or nothing.
Just the way I play it, Jeremy.

17:04.834 --> 17:07.209
Bloody hell! I'll call you back.

17:07.751 --> 17:09.417
Patricia Deville.

17:10.459 --> 17:11.501
Don't tell me.

17:12.834 --> 17:14.709
- Sorry, it's gone.
- You're joking?

17:14.834 --> 17:17.459
We did live together
for over two and a half years.

17:18.334 --> 17:19.876
We certainly did.

17:20.001 --> 17:21.584
What are you doing here?

17:21.709 --> 17:24.834
Oh, you know, work, meetings.
Busy, busy. You know how it is.

17:24.959 --> 17:28.668
- What are you doing here?
- I'm a journalist now. I work here.

17:28.751 --> 17:30.251
Get out of town!

17:31.543 --> 17:35.251
That's amazing. Actually,
I might just have something for you.

17:35.376 --> 17:36.793
Is it weed killer?

17:37.418 --> 17:39.793
- Hmm?
- You left our house to get weed killer...

17:39.876 --> 17:43.084
...24 years ago. I haven't seen you since.

17:43.251 --> 17:46.834
- I see what you're doing.
- The weeds are really out of control now.

17:46.959 --> 17:49.876
- I explained my departure in the letters.
- The letters?

17:50.001 --> 17:52.418
Yeah, the letters that
you failed to respond to.

17:55.251 --> 17:57.668
- Let's not do this.
- Let's not even go there.

17:57.751 --> 18:01.126
I'm only here for a couple of days
and I'm about to launch something big.

18:01.334 --> 18:04.626
- I was thinking...
- You want to use me for publicity, right?

18:04.709 --> 18:06.501
You need some profile. Is that it?

18:06.626 --> 18:09.459
Way off, Pat.
I can't talk about the details right now.

18:09.626 --> 18:12.918
Let's just say,
it's an interesting little acting job.

18:13.043 --> 18:15.459
Right. I thought maybe you'd given up acting.

18:15.584 --> 18:17.793
Obviously didn't catch me
in Midsummer Murders.

18:17.959 --> 18:20.376
That's what made me think you'd given up.

18:21.501 --> 18:23.543
Pow! Ooh, you got me.

18:23.626 --> 18:26.084
Look at this.
Laughin' and a-jokin' like old times.

18:26.293 --> 18:27.834
Got to run.

18:27.959 --> 18:31.918
You'd be foolish to walk away from what
I'm about to plonk down on the table.

18:32.001 --> 18:33.959
I'm a serious journalist now.

18:34.043 --> 18:36.709
Maybe catching
the psychotic killer, Paul Melly,

18:36.793 --> 18:38.959
isn't a serious enough story for you.

18:44.584 --> 18:47.709
There's a press gag on that case.
How do you know about it?

18:47.793 --> 18:52.459
Why don't we grab a bite
and I'll give you the full exposé?

18:52.584 --> 18:56.084
- You mean exclusive.
- Whatever you say.

18:57.126 --> 18:59.751
- Let's talk later.
- Let's do that.

19:07.251 --> 19:09.459
Still got it. Ha-ha!

19:09.543 --> 19:10.709
Shit!

19:16.459 --> 19:19.251
- Where is he?
- He said he was meditating.

19:20.918 --> 19:23.418
Went pretty deep, threw in a bit of Capoeira.

19:24.543 --> 19:25.876
Right.

19:26.001 --> 19:27.418
Let's nail this mother!

19:27.543 --> 19:28.751
Sorry.

19:30.001 --> 19:32.001
The suspect's name is Paul Melly,

19:32.126 --> 19:35.751
and he might be using the island's
extensive mine system to evade capture.

19:35.876 --> 19:37.709
Mine system? Clever bugger.

19:37.834 --> 19:39.918
Do you recognise him, Richard?

19:40.751 --> 19:43.709
Oh, my God. It's my agent.

19:43.793 --> 19:45.668
Only joking!

19:45.751 --> 19:48.584
Could I get an Americano with hot milk?

19:48.709 --> 19:51.876
Tragically, the boy's parents were killed
in a car crash when he was nine.

19:52.001 --> 19:54.834
And when he was informed,
he was watching Mindhorn,

19:54.959 --> 19:58.209
so he has developed a sort
of morbid obsession with the show.

19:58.334 --> 20:00.501
Could've been worse,
could've been Windjammer.

20:00.626 --> 20:03.293
Yeah, well, he is calling
in 15 minutes, Richard,

20:03.418 --> 20:06.626
and... he's calling himself the Kestrel.

20:06.709 --> 20:10.126
Now, he might make
some sort of kestrel noises.

20:10.293 --> 20:11.543
Kestrel noises, good.

20:11.668 --> 20:14.668
Look, I've got friends coming.
Can I put a list on reception?

20:14.751 --> 20:17.751
- A list at reception?
- Yeah, Jeffrey Moncrief plus one.

20:17.876 --> 20:19.918
This is Chief Inspector Newson.

20:20.043 --> 20:23.709
Ah, the head honcho.
El honcherino. The Big Cheese.

20:23.834 --> 20:26.501
- You look familiar. Did we golf?
- No.

20:26.584 --> 20:29.418
I wanted to talk to you
about the press conference.

20:29.543 --> 20:31.629
We could co-host, but I'm camera trained.

20:31.709 --> 20:34.876
Sometimes, police can come across
as weird and sweaty-looking.

20:35.001 --> 20:38.834
Mr Thorncroft, you are aware
of the seriousness of the situation?

20:38.959 --> 20:41.959
Big time. Yes, indeed.
We'll hash out the details later.

20:42.084 --> 20:45.668
- Is there a dressing room?
- You know how phones work, right?

20:45.751 --> 20:48.459
- Do you know how acting works?
- I'm not interested.

20:48.584 --> 20:50.251
We all have our process.

20:50.376 --> 20:53.668
Sometimes an item of clothing
or footwear can define a character.

20:53.751 --> 20:55.751
You have your costume, I have mine.

20:55.876 --> 20:57.671
This isn't a costume.

20:57.751 --> 21:01.376
This is an officially sanctioned uniform
denoting rank and civic responsibility.

21:01.543 --> 21:04.751
It's still a kind of costume.
You put it on to play the Chief.

21:04.876 --> 21:08.209
Then later on, you take it off
when you go home to your wife.

21:08.293 --> 21:09.709
Or maybe you don't.

21:09.876 --> 21:11.918
- All the world's a stage.
- No, it isn't.

21:12.043 --> 21:13.876
A young woman has been murdered.

21:14.043 --> 21:17.459
We're trying to catch her killer
before he does it again.

21:17.584 --> 21:19.709
- Okay.
- Do you want to get changed in here?

21:20.834 --> 21:23.668
What's wrong with him? Lost his truncheon?

21:25.376 --> 21:29.043
Jeff, the cops are being a bit
bloody stingy with their door policy.

21:29.209 --> 21:30.376
Ah, bastards!

21:30.501 --> 21:34.709
We'll have to get the photographer
to take the photos outside, looking in.

21:34.834 --> 21:37.376
I'm on the first floor.
I'll favour the north side.

21:37.501 --> 21:39.084
'North windows. Got it.'

21:39.251 --> 21:42.084
- 'Are you nearly here?'
- I'm running a tad late, Richie.

21:42.251 --> 21:44.959
I had to tidy up the Glendale account.

21:45.084 --> 21:47.334
Will you speed things up there, Barbara?

21:47.459 --> 21:50.751
'It's great to be heading back
to the big time with you, Richie.'

21:50.876 --> 21:54.501
- 'Wish me luck.'
- You are going to be great, Richie.

21:54.668 --> 21:56.084
Tits and teeth, eh?

21:59.501 --> 22:01.876
Hello, old friend.

22:30.084 --> 22:31.668
- Richard.
- Bainesy.

22:31.751 --> 22:34.709
When Melly calls,
stay in character at all times.

22:34.793 --> 22:36.876
Don't worry. When I go in, I go deep.

22:37.001 --> 22:39.709
Ah, the old two-way mirrors.
I love these things.

22:41.043 --> 22:44.001
Okay, here's a list of prompts.
Just stick to script.

22:44.084 --> 22:46.418
And avoid any of these trigger words.

22:46.543 --> 22:50.293
"Insane, nutjob, mental."
Blah, blah, blah, usual stuff.

22:50.418 --> 22:52.293
- This the phone?
- That is the phone.

22:52.376 --> 22:53.584
- Great.
- Yeah.

22:57.834 --> 22:59.043
Yeah.

23:00.501 --> 23:02.626
It's going to be okay.

23:11.584 --> 23:13.751
If you could just keep it in the cradle.

23:13.876 --> 23:15.709
Just connecting with the props.

23:15.834 --> 23:19.876
So, when he calls,
keep him on the line, keep him talking,

23:20.501 --> 23:22.709
arrange to meet and we'll take it from there.

23:23.751 --> 23:26.629
Here you go, Richard.
I couldn't find any Manuka honey.

23:26.709 --> 23:29.126
- Oh. Two teabags, though?
- Yeah, like you said.

23:29.293 --> 23:31.709
Good. A little tip I picked up
from Sean Bean.

23:31.793 --> 23:33.876
Double-bag Bean, we called him. The Bean Bag!

23:38.501 --> 23:40.126
This is it.

23:40.293 --> 23:42.293
Shoes going on.

23:44.834 --> 23:46.668
Shoes on.

23:48.334 --> 23:50.959
Yeah, whenever you're ready, Richard.

24:01.293 --> 24:04.001
Yep, whenever you're ready, Richard.

24:06.126 --> 24:07.709
Oh, Jesus! Answer it.

24:07.793 --> 24:11.251
- Fucking clown!
- Mindhorn makes people wait.

24:11.376 --> 24:14.626
And when they wait, they become angry
and they become vulnerable,

24:14.709 --> 24:18.043
and when they're vulnerable,
they make mistakes.

24:18.209 --> 24:20.918
Yo, what's going down?

24:21.043 --> 24:22.709
Hello? Hello?

24:22.793 --> 24:24.709
He's hung up.

24:24.834 --> 24:27.126
You might want to try 1471.

24:29.001 --> 24:30.751
Yo, what's going down, Kestrel?

24:30.918 --> 24:34.293
- 'Do you remember me?'
- Course I do. What do you want, sir?

24:34.418 --> 24:38.293
- 'I have something for you, Mindhorn.'
- That's nice. Is it my birthday?

24:38.418 --> 24:40.376
He's close, maybe in a phone box.

24:40.501 --> 24:43.501
The only present I'm interested in
is the truth.

24:43.626 --> 24:47.834
And don't bother wrapping it,
because I don't care for pretty packaging.

24:47.959 --> 24:50.376
'How do I know this is really you?'

24:50.501 --> 24:54.793
How do I know it's really you, Kestrel,
and not some insane, mental nutjob?

24:55.709 --> 24:58.876
'Why would you say that? I'm the Kestrel!'

25:01.751 --> 25:05.751
- 'More people are going to die.'
- We're all going to die. Get over it.

25:05.876 --> 25:08.209
Some with a bang, some with a whimper,

25:08.376 --> 25:10.459
some with a weird wasting disease.

25:12.751 --> 25:15.459
- 'Oh, it really is you.'
- Gold star, Kestrel.

25:15.584 --> 25:18.376
Now tell me something
I don't already bloody know.

25:18.501 --> 25:23.209
'You want to catch Katya's killer,
don't you? Well, get this...

25:24.543 --> 25:26.709
'What's that noise?
Is there anyone else there?

25:26.834 --> 25:28.876
Negative, sir. Mindhorn works alone.

25:29.001 --> 25:32.668
Listen, big guy, why don't we grab
some face-to-face time?

25:32.751 --> 25:35.209
- Where are you calling from?
- 'No, it's not safe.

25:35.334 --> 25:37.709
'The piggies are listening.
You know the quarry?'

25:37.793 --> 25:40.584
- Of course I know.
- 'Good. I'll meet you outside it.'

25:40.709 --> 25:42.334
- See you there.
- 'Come alone.'

25:42.459 --> 25:44.459
- I always do.
- Which quarry?

25:44.584 --> 25:46.293
- No idea. Did you get a trace?
- No.

25:46.376 --> 25:49.209
What kind of an outfit is this?
That is a rookie mistake.

25:49.834 --> 25:50.918
Hey.

25:51.084 --> 25:55.959
- You were meant to keep him on the line.
- That's not the way the scene played out.

25:56.084 --> 25:59.834
- There's a quarry at Vazon Edge.
- That's where we did all our car chases.

25:59.918 --> 26:02.584
That's where he'll be. Go get him, team.

26:03.459 --> 26:06.043
- Prick!
- Oh, dear.

26:06.126 --> 26:07.918
Someone's not a happy bunny.

26:08.043 --> 26:10.834
I remember now, it was his wife
I used to play golf with,

26:10.959 --> 26:12.751
if you catch my drift.

26:14.251 --> 26:16.834
Hole in one. Didn't think he knew.

26:16.959 --> 26:20.334
Er... Why did Melly say outside the quarry?

26:21.709 --> 26:25.293
Do you think "the quarry" meant
something different on Mindhorn?

26:25.459 --> 26:28.376
A quarry's a quarry.
I wouldn't overthink these things.

26:28.501 --> 26:30.501
Just going to go and drain the python.

26:31.084 --> 26:33.959
Then we can have a natter
about the press conference.

26:35.876 --> 26:38.709
'ETA to Vazon Edge quarry: four minutes.'

26:47.043 --> 26:50.626
All cars, the quarry is the police station.
Melly is here. Over.

26:50.709 --> 26:53.418
'Roger that. Diverting.'

26:53.584 --> 26:56.459
Turn around. Do it now!

26:56.584 --> 27:00.251
- What are you doing?
- Move the fucking van, you prick!

27:01.084 --> 27:02.334
Richard!

27:13.918 --> 27:18.293
Thorncroft's gone. I repeat,
I have lost eyes on Thorncroft.

27:18.418 --> 27:19.376
Shit.

27:19.501 --> 27:21.918
Okay, you got the action shot
through the window.

27:22.043 --> 27:24.584
- Why don't we hit the park?
- Good plan.

27:24.709 --> 27:28.793
'Thorncroft may be in danger.
The suspect was outside the station.'

27:29.459 --> 27:31.793
That'd be a great backdrop. I'll be here.

27:31.918 --> 27:33.876
Obviously I'll pull this in on the day.

27:34.001 --> 27:37.126
- Good to go.
- Your face has fallen down.

27:37.334 --> 27:40.251
- It's all baggy.
- Yeah. Do you mind? We all age.

27:40.376 --> 27:44.834
Use back light, soften the focus.
I'm not going to tell you your job. Jesus!

27:44.959 --> 27:46.876
- Jeff?
- 'Richie, where are you?'

27:47.001 --> 27:49.959
I'm with the photographer.
He's a bit weird. Where are you?

27:50.084 --> 27:52.668
'I'm with the photographer
outside the station.'

27:52.751 --> 27:54.709
You must have made quite an impression.

27:54.834 --> 27:57.709
There's police running about
like headless chickens.

28:00.376 --> 28:03.459
'Are you celebrating already? Richie?'

28:04.418 --> 28:06.834
Clever Mindhorn.

28:06.918 --> 28:09.209
It's time.

28:10.501 --> 28:14.418
Time for the apocalypse of justice.

28:19.251 --> 28:21.376
Aargh! Ooh!

28:33.709 --> 28:35.251
Mindhorn.

28:35.376 --> 28:37.126
Please, no.

28:37.293 --> 28:39.584
Look into my eyes.

28:40.834 --> 28:43.543
- Can you see the truth?
- Yeah.

28:43.668 --> 28:46.793
Did you receive the evidence
I sent to your house?

28:46.918 --> 28:48.876
Yes, definitely.

28:49.001 --> 28:51.209
You did? Then you know I'm innocent.

28:51.376 --> 28:53.751
- Are you on the case?
- Yes, sir.

29:02.293 --> 29:06.084
- It's pretend, see?
- Melly, step away from the actor.

29:06.251 --> 29:09.459
- Stay down, Richard.
- See you at the wheel, Mindhorn.

29:09.584 --> 29:11.918
Shoot him! Shoot him in the head!

29:23.668 --> 29:28.751
My next guest is a celebrated actor
and now an award-winning writer.

29:28.876 --> 29:31.501
Richard Thorncroft, welcome to the show.

29:31.626 --> 29:33.043
Hello.

29:33.209 --> 29:36.793
So you've finished your book,
which is not only deeply entertaining,

29:36.918 --> 29:40.876
it is also the first actor's autobiography
to be nominated for a Booker Prize.

29:41.668 --> 29:44.834
You've embarked on a production
of Hamlet with Kenneth Branagh,

29:44.959 --> 29:49.251
and become a hero by making this island
safe for vulnerable women like myself.

29:49.376 --> 29:51.418
- You're welcome.
- Thank you.

29:52.126 --> 29:55.043
Apparently, after the shock
of the accident, your hair grew back.

29:55.209 --> 29:58.459
Yes, it's a medical phenomenon
known as follicle neogenesis.

29:58.584 --> 30:01.293
'And conversely,
when I heard about the accident,

30:01.418 --> 30:02.751
'all my hair fell out.'

30:02.876 --> 30:06.001
Thanks, Ken, but we're talking
about Richard at the moment.

30:06.126 --> 30:09.459
- 'Oh, I'm so sorry. Sorry, Rich.'
- No probs, Ken.

30:09.584 --> 30:11.293
'Okay.'

30:11.418 --> 30:14.626
- May I?
- Fill your boots.

30:15.126 --> 30:17.376
- Mm, that's it.
- Oh.

30:17.501 --> 30:18.918
Don't be afraid.

30:19.584 --> 30:24.834
'With that audition, he changed the way
that people think about making art.

30:25.709 --> 30:27.959
'Politically, he's become very important.

30:28.126 --> 30:30.418
'For me, there is no one else.

30:30.543 --> 30:35.043
'It's, like, Mandela, Ben Kingsley,
and then there is Richard.'

30:35.209 --> 30:36.543
Richard...

30:36.668 --> 30:40.293
I'm going to give you the best
Manx Day you've ever had.

30:42.001 --> 30:45.584
'Of course, the parade is
at the heart of Manx Day.

30:45.709 --> 30:48.209
'Always has been, always will be...'

30:57.668 --> 31:00.334
- Richie, baby!
- Jeffrey Moncrief!

31:00.501 --> 31:02.459
Good to see you!

31:03.584 --> 31:06.501
Look at you! The years have treated you well.

31:06.626 --> 31:09.543
- You too.
- Ah, don't lie. I'm a fucking wreck.

31:09.668 --> 31:11.793
- But who cares? You did it.
- That's right.

31:11.959 --> 31:14.001
They got him. You're a hero.

31:14.126 --> 31:16.501
I don't think you can smoke
in hospitals, Jeff.

31:16.584 --> 31:18.626
- Since when?
- Since the '50s.

31:18.709 --> 31:20.793
Oh, right. How did it go with Pat?

31:20.918 --> 31:23.709
Very well, actually.
I think we might just be in there.

31:23.793 --> 31:26.293
- I'll bet you are, eh?
- Strictly business.

31:26.418 --> 31:29.918
Oh, good, because when
your heroics hit the front page,

31:30.043 --> 31:32.084
you'll have minge coming out your arse.

31:32.209 --> 31:33.543
Ah, lovely.

31:33.668 --> 31:35.584
You remember these guys?

31:35.709 --> 31:38.126
"Nutmeg, the druid detective."

31:38.293 --> 31:41.834
"Moonshaft: he's blind,
he's black and he's back."

31:41.959 --> 31:43.543
They're out on DVD?

31:43.626 --> 31:46.043
Ten grand apiece they got,
and they were shite!

31:46.209 --> 31:49.459
Mindhorn had a metal eye
that could see the truth.

31:49.584 --> 31:52.543
What did Nutmeg have?
Some fucking joss sticks!

31:52.668 --> 31:56.459
- This is interesting, Jeff.
- Aye, and Pete thinks so too.

31:56.584 --> 32:00.459
He even wants to release it
through his production company.

32:00.584 --> 32:03.126
- Pete Easterman?
- The Windjammer himself.

32:03.293 --> 32:06.293
This is a bad idea, Jeff.
Pete and I have a history.

32:06.418 --> 32:09.629
- Things have been said.
- That's all water under the bridge.

32:09.709 --> 32:13.043
Pete insisted you come
to his country club this evening.

32:13.209 --> 32:14.793
He wants to make it happen.

32:14.876 --> 32:18.418
Mindhorn, series one to three on DVD.

32:18.584 --> 32:21.459
How do you like those apples?

32:21.584 --> 32:24.001
This is actually a bloody good idea.

32:24.126 --> 32:26.334
I told you, eh? Lovely.

32:26.418 --> 32:28.501
Seven o'clock, Jammer's club.

32:28.626 --> 32:33.709
Lock up your pussy.
The wolf pack is back on the prowl!

32:33.793 --> 32:36.418
It's a hospital, Jeff.
Keep it down a little bit.

32:36.543 --> 32:39.834
Flange ahoy, Richie. Flange ahoy.

32:39.918 --> 32:41.251
Yes, indeed.

32:42.293 --> 32:45.876
'More on that unfolding tragedy later.

32:46.001 --> 32:48.626
'Why does the Manx cat have no tail?

32:49.376 --> 32:53.043
'Some say they swam ashore
during a shipwreck in the 16th century.

32:53.209 --> 32:55.334
'Others say it's a genetic mutation...'

32:59.543 --> 33:01.459
Chekhov!

33:01.584 --> 33:02.918
Chekhov!

33:06.959 --> 33:09.418
- Hello.
- 'Hello, you.'

33:09.543 --> 33:11.084
- Hello, Richard.
- 'Hello.'

33:11.209 --> 33:13.459
So, you're still at the Heights.

33:14.376 --> 33:16.709
Yes, that's a good guess.

33:16.876 --> 33:18.626
So, I hear they caught Melly.

33:18.709 --> 33:22.834
'Yeah, that lunatic won't be troubling
the women of this island no more.

33:22.959 --> 33:25.543
- Quite a story.
- 'I like to think so.'

33:25.668 --> 33:28.418
Richard Thorncroft does something
for somebody else.

33:28.543 --> 33:30.626
'Pow. I walked into that.'

33:30.709 --> 33:34.459
- 'Where are you at the moment?'
- Oh, I'm staying at the Grand.

33:34.626 --> 33:38.501
That's where they've put me up,
anyway, you know, for my sins.

33:38.626 --> 33:43.293
It's nice, you know, a little suite.
One of those little... suites.

33:43.418 --> 33:47.126
Ooh, sorry, just slipped on a breakfast tray.

33:47.293 --> 33:49.584
Ha! Bloody room service.

33:49.668 --> 33:52.084
Yeah, I mean, who'd have thought

33:52.251 --> 33:56.334
you and I would've ended up drifting
like two lonely boats on the sea of life?

33:57.751 --> 34:01.001
Just two boats who crossed once before

34:01.084 --> 34:03.876
and are now crossing again
on the return charter,

34:04.001 --> 34:07.376
looking for that safe harbour,
that magical other person.

34:07.501 --> 34:11.543
That other person can be staring you
in the face and you never even realise it.

34:11.668 --> 34:12.668
Hey, Richie.

34:15.126 --> 34:17.543
- Clive.
- Wow!

34:17.668 --> 34:20.626
- Wow, so good to see you!
- It's so good to see you.

34:20.708 --> 34:22.918
What are you doing in my garden, man?

34:23.001 --> 34:25.418
- What are you doing in the garden?
- I live here.

34:25.543 --> 34:28.126
Yeah... What, in the garden?

34:28.251 --> 34:31.208
No, silly. I live here with Pat.

34:31.333 --> 34:34.126
We've been together
for many years now, since you left.

34:34.293 --> 34:35.751
- You know that, right?
- Yeah.

34:35.876 --> 34:38.043
- You're joking with me.
- That's old news.

34:38.251 --> 34:39.583
- Joke.
- Oh, wow!

